(17, 53, 53, '{\"en\":\"Natural gas\",\"ar\":\"\\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a\"}', 'post', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'publish', 0, NULL, NULL, 'Natural-gas.jpg', NULL, '{\"en\":\"One of the most important and useful fuels on our planet is natural gas. It meets about 23% of the world\'s energy needs, and it appears that the importance of \\\"natural gas\\\" will increase even more in the coming years, as the International Energy Agency expects 40% growth in natural gas demand by 2040.\",\"ar\":\"\\u0623\\u062d\\u062f \\u0623\\u0647\\u0645 \\u0623\\u0646\\u0648\\u0627\\u0639 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0648\\u0642\\u0648\\u062f \\u0648\\u0623\\u0643\\u062b\\u0631\\u0647\\u0627 \\u0641\\u0627\\u0626\\u062f\\u0629 \\u0639\\u0644\\u0649 \\u0643\\u0648\\u0643\\u0628\\u0646\\u0627 \\u0647\\u0648 \\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a. \\u0625\\u0646\\u0647\\u0627 \\u062a\\u0644\\u0628\\u064a \\u062d\\u0648\\u0627\\u0644\\u064a 23\\u066a \\u0645\\u0646 \\u0627\\u062d\\u062a\\u064a\\u0627\\u062c\\u0627\\u062a \\u0627\\u0644\\u0639\\u0627\\u0644\\u0645 \\u0645\\u0646 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0627\\u0642\\u0629\\u060c \\u0648\\u064a\\u0628\\u062f\\u0648 \\u0623\\u0646 \\u0623\\u0647\\u0645\\u064a\\u0629 \\\"\\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a \\\" \\u0633\\u062a\\u0632\\u062f\\u0627\\u062f \\u0623\\u0643\\u062b\\u0631 \\u0641\\u064a \\u0627\\u0644\\u0633\\u0646\\u0648\\u0627\\u062a \\u0627\\u0644\\u0642\\u0627\\u062f\\u0645\\u0629\\u060c \\u062d\\u064a\\u062b \\u062a\\u062a\\u0648\\u0642\\u0639 \\u0648\\u0643\\u0627\\u0644\\u0629 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0627\\u0642\\u0629 \\u0627\\u0644\\u062f\\u0648\\u0644\\u064a\\u0629 \\u0646\\u0645\\u0648\\u0627\\u064b \\u0628\\u0646\\u0633\\u0628\\u0629 40\\u066a \\u0641\\u064a \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0644\\u0628 \\u0639\\u0644\\u0649 \\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a \\u0628\\u062d\\u0644\\u0648\\u0644 \\u0639\\u0627\\u0645 2040.\"}', '{\"en\":\"<p>One of the most important and useful fuels on our planet is natural gas. It meets about 23% of the world\'s energy needs, and it appears that the importance of \\\"natural gas\\\" will increase even more in the coming years, as the International Energy Agency expects 40% growth in natural gas demand by 2040.<\\/p><p>\\ud83d\\udcccWhat is natural gas?<\\/p><p>Natural gas is a fossil energy source formed deep beneath the Earth\'s surface. Natural gas contains many different compounds. The largest component of natural gas is methane, which is a compound with one carbon atom and four hydrogen (CH4) atoms.<\\/p><p>Natural gas also contains smaller amounts of liquids (NGL, which are also hydrocarbon liquids) and non-hydrocarbon gases, such as carbon dioxide and water vapor. We use natural gas as fuel and to produce energy and chemicals.<\\/p><p>Millions to hundreds of millions of years ago, and over long periods of time, plant and animal remains accumulated in thick layers of the Earth\'s surface and ocean floor, sometimes mixed with sand, clay, and calcium carbonate. Over time, these layers are buried under sand, mud, and rocks.<\\/p><p>Pressure and heat have turned some of these substances rich in carbon and hydrogen into coal, some into oil, and some into natural gas.<\\/p><p>Types of natural gas<\\/p><p>In some places, natural gas has moved in large crevices and spaces between the overhanging rock layers. The natural gas present in these types of formations is sometimes called conventional natural gas.<\\/p><p>Elsewhere, natural gas occurs in small pores (spaces) in some shales, sandstones, and other sedimentary rock formations. This natural gas is called shale gas and it is sometimes called unconventional natural gas.<\\/p><p>The deposits of blue fuels are often mixed - oil and natural gas. This type of natural gas is called Associated Natural Gas<\\/p><p>The largest natural gas producer in the world<\\/p><p>The largest natural gas producing countries in the world are:<\\/p><p>1. United States of America<\\/p><p>2 Russia<\\/p><p>3. Iran<\\/p><p>4 Canada<\\/p><p>5 - The State of Qatar<\\/p><p>6 China<\\/p><p>7 Norway<\\/p><p>8 Australia<\\/p><p>9- Kingdom of Saudi Arabia<\\/p><p>10 Algeria<\\/p><p>\\ud83d\\udccc What are the factors for changing the price of natural gas?<\\/p><p>Raw materials such as oil and gas are the engines of the world. Our lives would not be the same without oil and natural gas.<\\/p><p>This dependence on oil and natural gas makes it easy to determine price fluctuations in the oil and gas industry for consumers. The fluctuations can be seen more easily at the gas station when you fill up your car.<\\/p><p>How can you benefit from the changes in the price of natural gas?<\\/p><p>These price changes may seem arbitrary, but there are many factors that influence the increase or decrease in the price of oil and gas. The composition of volatile prices for natural gas is much more than supply and demand. Here are some of the main factors that affect it:<\\/p><p>\\u2714 cyclical factors. Traditionally, the demand for natural gas is cyclical and seasonal, being higher in the winter (due to heating) and lowest in the summer. This leads to a jump in gas demand in January and February, as well as a similar drop in July and August. However, with the relatively recent trend of using natural gas to generate electricity, this cyclical behavior has changed slightly. Demand for natural gas continues to decline in the summer, but now natural gas is used to produce electricity to power commercial and residential refrigeration. This leads to a new jump in demand in the summer. However, the summer jump is smaller than the winter\'s elevation, but it is not insignificant.<\\/p><p>Switch between fuels. Most commercial consumers and households only use natural gas to meet their energy needs, but some industrial consumers and public utilities that generate electricity have the ability to switch between different fuels. This is one of the cases where price affects demand, rather than demand affects the price of natural gas. For example, if the electric generator considers the price of natural gas too high, it may switch to cheaper fuel such as coal, which reduces the demand for natural gas.<\\/p><p>Economy. The state of the economy could also affect the demand for natural gas. If the economy is doing well, industrial production will increase, which will lead to an increase in the demand for natural gas. In weak economic periods, industrial production declines, which leads to lower gas demand.<\\/p><p>Stock levels. The Energy Information Administration publishes a weekly report detailing the ongoing storage of natural gas. Natural gas prices often change as a result of this report. If there is a decrease in inventories greater than expected or the volume added in storage after the last report is smaller, then prices may rise. If the opposite happens, prices usually drop.<\\/p><p>technological improvement. Advances in technologies that facilitate gas extraction, as well as innovations in the use of natural gas, such as the use of natural gas as an alternative fuel for vehicles, increase the volume of gas produced and find a good use for it.<\\/p><p>Natural disasters and crises. If a natural disaster or crisis threatens natural gas supplies, gas price volatility will certainly increase. Political and economic crises can cause such volatility.<\\/p><p>Damage to the infrastructure of suppliers. Serious damage to the infrastructure for the extraction and transportation of natural gas may result from a change in supply, respectively, in the current price of natural gas.<\\/p><p>It is important to note that as an end user, you receive one price for natural gas, and that in global financial markets it may be different. The price of natural gas contracts on global markets is due to its natural state, which comes out of the ground. While there may be costs for refining, transportation and various fees.<\\/p><p>However, in most cases<\\/p>\",\"ar\":\"<p>\\u0623\\u062d\\u062f \\u0623\\u0647\\u0645 \\u0623\\u0646\\u0648\\u0627\\u0639 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0648\\u0642\\u0648\\u062f \\u0648\\u0623\\u0643\\u062b\\u0631\\u0647\\u0627 \\u0641\\u0627\\u0626\\u062f\\u0629 \\u0639\\u0644\\u0649 \\u0643\\u0648\\u0643\\u0628\\u0646\\u0627 \\u0647\\u0648 \\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a. \\u0625\\u0646\\u0647\\u0627 \\u062a\\u0644\\u0628\\u064a \\u062d\\u0648\\u0627\\u0644\\u064a 23\\u066a \\u0645\\u0646 \\u0627\\u062d\\u062a\\u064a\\u0627\\u062c\\u0627\\u062a \\u0627\\u0644\\u0639\\u0627\\u0644\\u0645 \\u0645\\u0646 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0627\\u0642\\u0629\\u060c \\u0648\\u064a\\u0628\\u062f\\u0648 \\u0623\\u0646 \\u0623\\u0647\\u0645\\u064a\\u0629 \\\"\\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a \\\" \\u0633\\u062a\\u0632\\u062f\\u0627\\u062f \\u0623\\u0643\\u062b\\u0631 \\u0641\\u064a \\u0627\\u0644\\u0633\\u0646\\u0648\\u0627\\u062a \\u0627\\u0644\\u0642\\u0627\\u062f\\u0645\\u0629\\u060c \\u062d\\u064a\\u062b \\u062a\\u062a\\u0648\\u0642\\u0639 \\u0648\\u0643\\u0627\\u0644\\u0629 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0627\\u0642\\u0629 \\u0627\\u0644\\u062f\\u0648\\u0644\\u064a\\u0629 \\u0646\\u0645\\u0648\\u0627\\u064b \\u0628\\u0646\\u0633\\u0628\\u0629 40\\u066a \\u0641\\u064a \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0644\\u0628 \\u0639\\u0644\\u0649 \\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a \\u0628\\u062d\\u0644\\u0648\\u0644 \\u0639\\u0627\\u0645 2040.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\ud83d\\udccc\\u0645\\u0627 \\u0647\\u0648 \\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a\\u061f<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u0627\\u0644\\u063a\\u0627\\u0632 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0637\\u0628\\u064a\\u0639\\u064a \\u0647\\u0648 \\u0645\\u0635\\u062f\\u0631 \\u0637\\u0627\\u0642\\u062